description: Disconnect the existing battery. Using clip leads from a separate, verified 12 V bench supply or known-good battery pack, connect directly to the metal battery contacts inside the power supply module (bypassing the plastic battery holder if possible). Confirm polarity, then energize and measure voltage directly at those contacts and observe whether the green PSU LED turns on. Report the measured voltage at the contacts and at the LED/resistor node, and whether any LEDs or downstream indicators change state., outcome='Battery contacts and PSU output cables all measure 0.0 V with respect to ground, and the PSU status green LED and its series resistor also both sit at 0.0 V. The PSU status LED and all downstream power flow indicator LEDs, as well as the main load lamp and the internal indicator lamp, remain unlit with 0 V across them.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=475.0, cost_breakdown=[('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('open_peephole', 5.0), ('observe_component', 10.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Observe -> Power supply module internal wiring from battery contacts to output cables,
description: With all external cables disconnected from the power supply module, visually inspect (via any accessible panel or by carefully opening the casing if allowed) how the two internal wires from the battery contacts are routed to the LED/resistor branch and to the two output cables. Look specifically for an open connection, miswired joint, missing link between the battery circuit and the output cabling, or an internal common reference/ground that your external measurement might be tied to instead of the floating 12 V source., outcome='The requested action could not be mapped to any recognized diagnostic operation. Only actions from the available action list are supported (e.g. measure_voltage, test_continuity, inspect_connections, verify_repair, …).\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=0.0, cost_breakdown=[], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Observe -> Power supply module internal wiring and connectors,
description: Carefully open or view through the available inspection access on the power supply module and perform a detailed visual inspection of the internal wiring from the battery contacts to the LED/resistor branch and to the outgoing cables, as well as any internal connectors or PCB traces. Look for obvious opens, broken or unsoldered wires, missing jumpers, loose internal plug-in connectors, or signs that the battery terminals are not actually connected to the rest of the circuit., outcome='The inspection panel could not be opened or closed because the Power Supply Cube enclosure is neither openable nor closeable. The battery shows an internal fault with 0.0 V, while the PSU status LED, its resistor, the battery internal resistor, and both PSU output cables show no observable internal faults and are all reported as connected. No polarity inversion is indicated between the PSU Output Cable (+) and PSU Output Cable (−).\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=70.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('close_inspection_panel', 5.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Power supply module output cables and downstream series path,
description: With the now-good battery installed in the power supply module and all modules connected as in normal operation, measure the voltage directly on the two PSU output terminals/cables. Then move stepwise down the series chain: measure the voltage between the two terminals at the input of control module 1, then at its output, and similarly at the input and output of each subsequent control module up to the load module. Record at which point (between which two modules) the measured voltage first drops from approximately 12 V to 0 V., outcome='The PSU output shows ~12 V across its (+) and (−) cables, and this ~12 V is present across the input and output of control modules 1 and 2. The first point where the measured voltage between the module terminals drops from ~12 V to ~0 V is across control module 3 (between its input (+)/input (−) and especially between its output (+)/output (−)), and it remains ~0 V for all subsequent modules and at the load.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=720.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Control module 3 switch and indicator LED branch,
description: With the system powered and all modules connected, focus on control module 3. First, verify with a meter that ~12 V is present between its input (+) and input (−) terminals. Then, with the module switch in the ON position, measure (a) the voltage across the switch terminals, (b) the voltage from the input (+) to the output (+), and from input (−) to output (−), and (c) the voltage across the red indicator LED+series resistor inside the module. This will determine whether CM3 is internally open, shorted, or miswired and whether its indicator branch is receiving 12 V., outcome='Control Input Cable (+) 3 has ~12 V present, while Control Input Cable (−) 3 is near 0 V, confirming the expected input differential. The downstream switch terminals, output cables (+/−), LED, and series resistor in Control Module 3 are all near 0 V, and a nearby anomaly indicates the far end of Control Input Cable (+) 3 is disconnected from Control Switch 3.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=160.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('close_switch', 10.0), ('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
